{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17563935","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17563935"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T23:07:04+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T23:07:04+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16915"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"16915","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/16915"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.15,0.17,0.06,0.53,0.09]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9605"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"67680"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"9605","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/9605"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16915"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"53137"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"22"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1637"},{"type":"tags","id":"2320"},{"type":"tags","id":"5771"},{"type":"tags","id":"6356"},{"type":"tags","id":"11137"},{"type":"tags","id":"11149"},{"type":"tags","id":"12218"},{"type":"tags","id":"12801"},{"type":"tags","id":"12802"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"22673"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"67680","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/67680"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 16-year-old woman presents to the Emergency Department with severe cyclical lower abdominal pain that has been worsening over the past year. She reached menarche at age 13 and has regular periods. She has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications. On examination, she appears well with vital signs within normal limits. There is tenderness in the left iliac fossa without peritonism. Transvaginal ultrasound reveals a normal right-sided uterine cavity with endometrial lining, and a left-sided non-communicating uterine horn containing old blood. These findings are confirmed on magnetic resonance imaging.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely long-term complication of this condition?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Uterine rupture","Pelvic inflammatory disease","Ovarian cysts","Endometriosis","Menorrhagia"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with a unicornuate uterus with a non-communicating rudimentary horn, which is a type of M\u00fcllerian duct anomaly. These congenital malformations occur during embryological development when the M\u00fcllerian ducts fail to develop or fuse properly.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EEndometriosis\u003C/strong\u003E is the most likely long-term complication in this case. The functional endometrium within the non-communicating horn leads to retrograde menstruation, where menstrual blood flows backwards through the fallopian tubes into the peritoneal cavity. This retrograde flow of endometrial tissue can implant and grow on peritoneal surfaces, leading to endometriosis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EUterine rupture\u003C/strong\u003E is a rare but serious complication that can occur if pregnancy develops in the non-communicating horn. However, this is much less common than endometriosis as most pregnancies will implant in the normal communicating cavity.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPelvic inflammatory disease\u003C/strong\u003E is not directly related to M\u00fcllerian duct anomalies. It is typically caused by ascending infection with sexually transmitted organisms.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EOvarian cysts\u003C/strong\u003E are not specifically associated with uterine anomalies. While patients with endometriosis may develop endometriomas, these are a consequence of the endometriosis rather than the anatomical abnormality itself.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMenorrhagia\u003C/strong\u003E is not typically associated with a unicornuate uterus with non-communicating horn. The menstrual flow from the normal cavity should be regular, and blood in the non-communicating horn cannot exit through the cervix.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Non-communicating rudimentary horns are associated with retrograde menstruation leading to endometriosis","MRI is the gold standard imaging modality for diagnosing M\u00fcllerian duct anomalies","Patients with uterine anomalies are at increased risk of complications during pregnancy"],"references":["Piriyev E, R\u00f6mer T. Coincidence of uterine malformations and endometriosis: a clinically relevant problem? Arch Gynecol Obstet. 2020 Nov;302(5):1237-1241. doi: 10.1007/s00404-020-05750-9. Epub 2020 Aug 20. PMID: 32816056.","Jayaprakasan K, Ojha K. Diagnosis of Congenital Uterine Abnormalities: Practical Considerations. J Clin Med. 2022 Feb 25;11(5):1251. doi: 10.3390/jcm11051251. PMID: 35268343; PMCID: PMC8911320.","Akhtar MA, Saravelos SH, Li TC, Jayaprakasan K; on behalf of the Royal College of Obstetricians and Gynaecologists. Reproductive implications and management of congenital uterine anomalies. Scientific Impact Paper No. 62. BJOG. 2019 Nov 20; DOI: 10.1111/1471-0528.15968."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"53137"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16915"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"53137","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/53137"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-06T14:37:43+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-06T14:39:43+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9605"}},"